title: It isn't possible for a .NET package to use OnnxRuntime and have the application pick CPU or GPU

labels.name: feature request
labels.description: request for unsupported feature or enhancement

body:
Today, ML.NET builds an [Microsoft.ML.OnnxTransformer NuGet package](https://www.nuget.org/packages/Microsoft.ML.OnnxTransformer/) that depends on [Microsoft.ML.OnnxRuntime](https://www.nuget.org/packages/Microsoft.ML.OnnxRuntime/). This ML.NET package allows users to bring in pre-built onnx models into their ML.NET pipeline.

ML.NET users will reference `Microsoft.ML.OnnxTransformer`, and write their C# code to use their onnx model as necessary.

Everything works great, until the ML.NET user says "I want to execute that onnx model on a GPU in my ML.NET pipeline". Currently this isn't possible because of the way the OnnxRuntime NuGet packages are structured.

* `Microsoft.ML.OnnxRuntime`
    - Contains the C++ assemblies that are used to compute on a CPU
    - Contains the .NET managed assemblies containing the .NET APIs
* `Microsoft.ML.OnnxRuntime.GPU`
    - Contains the C++ assemblies that are used to compute on a GPU
    - Contains the .NET managed assemblies containing the .NET APIs

Because the ".NET managed assemblies" are in both packages, this causes issues when another .NET package wants to depend on the OnnxRuntime. That package (ML.NET in our case) needs to pick one of these in order to compile against the .NET API. However, once you pick one of these, the consumers of ML.NET are no longer able to change to the other package (CPU to GPU in our case).

Instead, we should really split the OnnxRuntime up into 3 packages:

* Managed APIs package
* Native CPU package
* Native GPU package

This would allow for ML.NET to reference the `Managed APIs package` all the time. But then allow for the user to pick the `Native CPU package` or the `Native GPU package` package, depending on their needs. This is the pattern followed by TF.NET - 

* Managed APIs package - https://www.nuget.org/packages/TensorFlow.NET/
* Native CPU package - https://www.nuget.org/packages/SciSharp.TensorFlow.Redist/
* Native GPU package - https://www.nuget.org/packages/SciSharp.TensorFlow.Redist-Windows-GPU/


## Alternative 
An common alternate approach to this that isn't feasible is to tell ML.NET to split the `Microsoft.ML.OnnxTransformer` into 2 packages: CPU and GPU. The reason this isn't feasible is because there are other packages that depend on `Microsoft.ML.OnnxTransformer`.
* https://www.nuget.org/packages/Microsoft.ML.DnnImageFeaturizer.AlexNet
* https://www.nuget.org/packages/Microsoft.ML.DnnImageFeaturizer.ResNet101
* https://www.nuget.org/packages/Microsoft.ML.DnnImageFeaturizer.ResNet50
* https://www.nuget.org/packages/Microsoft.ML.DnnImageFeaturizer.ResNet18

If we split `Microsoft.ML.OnnxTransformer` into 2 packages, each of the above would need to be split into 2. Then we would have 10 packages instead of 5, which just doesn't scale.

title: BitShift Not Implemented for uint8

labels.name: feature request
labels.description: request for unsupported feature or enhancement

body:
ONNX BitShift https://github.com/onnx/onnx/blob/master/docs/Operators.md#BitShift only supports unsigned input types (uint64, uint32, uint16, uint8).
PyTorch only has one unsigned type : uint8, but BitShift is not implemented in ONNX Runtime for uint8 type.
Would it be possible to add uint8 support, in order to use the BitShift operator in the PyTorch exporter, without the use of a subgraph?
